Jobs and Cron Job (Video - 2:21 - 2:39)

A Job runs a workload until it finishes successfully. 

A CronJob runs a Job automatically on a regular schedule.Unlike Deployments or ReplicaSets that keep apps running forever, Jobs and 
CronJobs are built for tasks that have a clear beginning and end.

1. Jobs
A Job creates one or more Pods and ensures that a target number of them complete successfully. Once the task finishes, the Pod stops 
running and goes into a completed state so you can inspect the logs.

Best for: One-time tasks like data migrations, database backups, or batch processing.
Self-Healing: If a Pod fails before finishing, the Job will start a new one to try again.

Job YAML Example

apiVersion: batch/v1
kind: Job
metadata:
  name: data-cleaner
spec:
  template:
    spec:
      containers:
      - name: cleaner
        image: alpine
        command: ["echo", "Data cleaning complete!"]
      restartPolicy: Never # Required: Prevents the container from looping forever
  backoffLimit: 4         # Number of retries before marking the Job as failed

2. CronJobs
A CronJob manages Jobs using a time-based schedule. It is exactly like the traditional Linux crontab tool, but it runs tasks inside a 
Kubernetes cluster.

Best for: Recurring tasks like weekly reports, nightly database cleanups, or hourly status checks.
The Schedule Format: It uses five fields to set the time: Minute Hour Day-of-month Month Day-of-week. For example, 0 0 * * * means "every
night at midnight."

CronJob YAML Example

apiVersion: batch/v1
kind: CronJob
metadata:
  name: nightly-backup
spec:
  schedule: "0 0 * * *"   # ⏰ Runs every single night at midnight
  jobTemplate:
    spec:
      template:
        spec:
          containers:
          - name: backup
            image: alpine
            command: ["echo", "Backup finished!"]
          restartPolicy: OnFailure

Useful Commands

Run a CronJob manually right now: 

kubectl create job --from=cronjob/nightly-backup manual-backup-run
See running Jobs: kubectl get jobs
See scheduled CronJobs: kubectl get cronjobs
